Factory vs. Abstract Factory Design Pattern

Below are the key differences between factory and abstract factory design pattern:

| Aspect                   | Factory Design Pattern                                | Abstract Factory Design Pattern                                                     |
| -----------------------  | ----------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1. Purpose               | Creates objects without specifying the exact class.   | Creates families of related objects without specifying their concrete classes.      | 
| 2. Complexity            | Less complex, focuses on a single product type.       | More complex, involves multiple related products.                                   |
| 3. Level of Abstraction  | Lower level of abstraction.                           | Higher level of abstraction.                                                        |
| 4. Class Hierarchy       | Involves a single factory method.                     | Involves multiple factory methods grouped under an abstract factory.                |
| 5. Object Creation       | One product per factory.                              | Multiple related products per factory.                                              |
| 6. Usage Scenario        | Useful when only one type of product is required.     | Useful when multiple types of related products are required.                        |
| 7. Flexibility           | Less flexible as it deals with a single product.      | More flexible as it deals with multiple related products.                           |
| 8. Code Maintainability  | Easier to maintain due to simplicity.                 | More complex but manageable with clear relationships among products                 |
| 9. Decoupling            | Decouples the code from the specific type of product. | Decouples the code from the family of products and their concrete implementations.  |
